Introduction This Rate Schedule WDT-ESF (BHD) (“Rate Schedule”) sets forth the rates, terms, and conditions for the provision of Wholesale Distribution Service by Versant Power (“Versant” or “Company”) to customers owning or operating eligible Electric Storage Facilities (“ESF”) directly interconnected to the Company’s Bangor Hydro District (“BHD”) Distribution System for purposes of delivering Wholesale Charging Load to such ESF. These services are intended for use by a Customer that will resell the energy back from its ESF to the ISO-NE market in a wholesale transaction, either as directed by ISO-NE or at the Customer’s discretion. The Company will deliver energy to a Customer’s Wholesale Charging Load under this Rate Schedule and the associated Service Agreement duly executed by Company and Customer. Company and Customer may be referred to individually as “Party” or collectively as “Parties”. This Rate Schedule sets forth different rates depending on whether the Customer elects (i) to charge its ESF in order to resell energy at a later time (Subschedule 1) or (ii) to be exclusively dispatched by ISO-NE in order to provide a service in the ISO-NE markets (Subschedule 2). Prior to the time the Customer begins taking service under this Rate Schedule, it must elect whether it will take service under Subschedule 1 or Subschedule 2, and it may change its election no more frequently than once per year through submission of a revised Customer Information Form (provided below). For the avoidance of doubt, a Customer taking service under Subschedule 1 may sell energy into the ISO-NE markets or be dispatched by ISO-NE. However, a Customer taking service under Subschedule 2 may only be dispatched by ISO-NE in order to provide a service in the ISO-NE markets and may not charge its ESF in order to resell energy at a later time. 1. Definitions 1.1 Customer. The entity taking WDS under this Rate Schedule. 1.2 Distribution System. The electric facilities classified as local distribution under FERC’s Order No. 888 seven-factor test and that are owned, controlled and operated by the Company and used to provide distribution services under this Rate Schedule. 1.3 Electric Storage Facility (“ESF”). A storage facility that is capable of absorbing electricity, storing it for a period of time, and thereafter dispatching the electricity to the electric grid, as the term is further defined in ISO-NE Tariff Section I.2.2. 1.4 FERC. The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC”). 1.5 Force Majeure. Any act of God, labor disturbance, act of the public enemy or terrorists, war, invasion, insurrection, riot, fire, storm or flood, ice, explosion, breakage or accident to machinery or equipment, any curtailment, order, regulation or restriction imposed by governmental military or lawfully established civilian authorities, or any other event that is beyond the reasonable control of the affected Company or Customer, and that the affected Company or Customer is unable to prevent or provide against by exercising commercially reasonable efforts. 1.6 Good Utility Practice. Any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region, including those practices required by Federal Power Act Section 215(a)(4). 1.7 Interconnection Service Agreement (“ISA”). The interconnection agreement entered into between the Customer and the Company, providing for parallel operation of the Customer’s ESF with the Distribution System pursuant to the Maine Public Utilities Commission Chapter 324, Small Generator Interconnection Standards, as amended from time to time. 1.8 ISO-NE. The New England Independent System Operator Inc., or any successor organization or entity, responsible for the continued operation of the New England Balancing Authority Area and the administration of the ISO-NE Tariff, subject to regulation by the FERC. 1.9 ISO-NE Tariff. The ISO-NE Transmission, Markets and Services Tariff and accompanying schedules and attachments, as modified and amended from time to time, and accepted by the FERC. 1.10 MPUC. The Maine Public Utilities Commission. 1.11 Monthly WDS Charge. The amount billed to the Customer for WDS in a billing month. 1.12 Point of Common Coupling (“PCC”). The point where the Customer’s local electric power system connects to the Distribution System. 1.13 Stand Alone ESF. A separately metered ESF owned or operated by the Customer at which the only sources of electrical load are the charging of the ESF technology or any Station Service Load, and which is not co-located behind the same PCC with any generation or any other customer loads that are electrically capable of being served by the ESF. 1.14 Station Service Load. The electric energy used for the heating, lighting, air-conditioning, and office equipment needs of the buildings at the ESF site, and for operating the electric equipment that is on the ESF site. Station Service Load shall be limited to load directly supporting the operation of the ESF, excluding Wholesale Charging Load. 1.15 Wholesale Charging Load. The wholesale energy used by the Customer’s ESF such that it can discharge and sell energy, capacity, ancillary services, or other FERC-jurisdictional services into the ISO-NE markets in accordance with ISO-NE Tariff, Section III.1.10.6. 1.16 Wholesale Distribution Service (“WDS”). Transportation of wholesale electric energy over the Distribution System to the Customer’s ESF. 1.17 Wholesale Distribution Service Agreement (“WDSA”). The agreement between the Company and Customer for the provision of WDS under this Rate Schedule and any amendments or supplements thereto. A pro forma WDSA is included as Attachment A to this Rate Schedule. 2. Availability 2.1 This Rate is available to Customers meeting the availability and character of service criteria listed under one of the following Versant rate schedules on file with the MPUC for service in the Bangor Hydro District: Business ECO Rate (Rate B-1), Business ECO Rate – Separate Meter (Rate B-5), Medium Power Rate – Primary (M-1), Medium Power Rate – Secondary (Rate M-2), Primary Power Large Rate (Rate D-4), and Transmission Power Rate (Rate T-1). Customers also must meet the eligibility criteria detailed below. 3. Eligibility 3.1 The Company will provide WDS under this Rate Schedule to Stand Alone ESF customers that: (i) are a party to an ISA with the Company; (ii) require the use of Company’s Distribution System to deliver energy to its Wholesale Charging Load and Critical Service Load; (iii) participate in the wholesale market to sell energy, capacity, ancillary services or other FERC-jurisdictional services; and (iv) are registered (directly or indirectly) with ISO-NE to participate in its markets. 3.2 Customer facilities with any end use loads not qualified as Wholesale Charging Load or Station Service and which are electrically capable of being served by the ESF shall not be eligible for service under this Rate Schedule. Storage co-located with generation behind the same PCC shall not be eligible for service under this Rate Schedule. Electric vehicle charging of any kind is not eligible for service under this Rate Schedule. 3.3 The Customer shall, at all times that it takes service under this Rate Schedule and the associated WDSA, at its own expense, be responsible for: (i) purchasing the wholesale energy being distributed to the ESF for purposes of serving Wholesale Charging Load and Critical Service Load, including allowances for losses; (ii) arranging for transmission and ancillary services, if required by the ISO- NE Tariff, for the delivery of said energy to the Distribution System; and (iii) arranging for state-jurisdictional retail service to serve its Station Service Load. 4. Obligations of the Customer 4.1 Subject to the terms and conditions of this Rate Schedule, the Company will provide Wholesale Distribution Service to any eligible Customer, provided that: (i) the Customer owns an ESF that is connected to the Distribution System and meets the eligibility criteria described above; (ii) the Customer meets the creditworthiness criteria set forth in Section 5; (iii) the Customer agrees to pay for any facilities pursuant to its ISA; and (iv) the Customer executes a WDSA for service under this Rate Schedule or requests in writing that the Company file a proposed unexecuted WDSA with FERC. 5. Creditworthiness 5.1 For the purpose of determining the ability of the Customer to meet its obligations related to service hereunder, the Company may require credit review procedures consistent with the ISO-NE Tariff, Schedule 21-VP Attachment Q-VP (Creditworthiness Guide). 6. Process for Obtaining WDS 6.1 Customer may receive service under this Rate Schedule if it demonstrates that it meets the eligibility criteria described in this Rate Schedule. A new customer seeking to receive service under this Rate Schedule must demonstrate alignment with the criteria prior to receiving permission to operate, with the exception of demonstrating registration as an Electric Storage Facility with ISO-NE, which may be demonstrated up to sixty (60) days after commencing service; otherwise such customer will be enrolled in the applicable retail rate until eligibility for WDS is demonstrated. 6.2 An eligible Customer requesting interconnection of an ESF to the Distribution System shall comply with MPUC Chapter 324, Small Generator Interconnection Standards, as may be in effect from time to time. 6.3 An eligible Customer requesting service under this Rate Schedule must submit an application to the Company as far as possible in advance of the month in which service is to commence. The Company may provide for an abbreviated application procedure when a Customer requests that an existing distribution service be converted to Wholesale Distribution Service under this Rate Schedule. Completed applications should be submitted electronically to the Company. These methods will provide a date-stamped record for establishing the priority of the application. A completed application shall provide all applicable information required to evaluate a request for WDS, including but not limited to the following: (i) The identity, address, telephone number and e-mail of the party requesting service; (ii) A statement that the party requesting service is, or will be upon commencement of service, a Customer under this Rate Schedule; (iii) The location of the PCC; (iv) A description of the Customer’s ESF; (v) A description of all loads that will be located at the site of the Customer’s ESF sufficient to demonstrate that on-site Wholesale Charging Load, Critical Service Load and Station Service Loads comply with the availability conditions of this Rate Schedule; (vi) A one-line diagram of all electrical equipment located at the site of the Customer’s ESF; (vii) A written demonstration that the Customer will have the necessary contractual arrangements or existing contracts in place to receive transmission service over the ISO-NE grid prior to the commencement of WDS under this Rate Schedule; (viii) A written demonstration that the Customer meets ISO-NE’s criteria for qualifying as an Electric Storage Facility, as described in the ISO-NE Tariff; (ix) The service commencement date and the term of the requested WDS; and (x) Such other information the Company reasonably requires to process the application. Unless the parties agree to a different time frame, the Company must acknowledge the application within ten (10) business days of receipt. The acknowledgment must include a date by which a response, including a WDSA, will be sent to the Customer. If an application fails to meet the requirements of this section, the Company shall notify the Customer requesting service within fifteen (15) business days of receipt and specify the reasons for such failure. Wherever possible, the Company will attempt to remedy deficiencies in the application through informal communications with the Customer. If such efforts are unsuccessful, the Company shall return the application to the Customer. The Company shall treat all information provided by the Customer consistent with the standards of conduct contained in 18 C.F.R. Part 358. 6.4 Failure of a Customer eligible for WDS to execute and return the WDSA or request the filing of an unexecuted WDSA pursuant to Section 3.1(iv) of this Rate Schedule within fifteen (15) business days after it is tendered by the Company will be deemed a withdrawal and termination of the application, and any deposit submitted shall be refunded with interest. Nothing herein limits the right of a Customer to file another application after such withdrawal and termination. 6.5 Either prior to the commencement of WDS or within sixty (60) days after such commencement, the Customer shall provide the Company with written evidence of the facility’s registration with ISO-NE as an Electric Storage Facility. A customer that fails to provide such evidence within the required period will be enrolled in the applicable retail rate until evidence of registration is provided. 7. Metering 7.1 Each ESF must meet the metering requirements necessary to qualify with ISO-NE as an Electric Storage Facility and to meet the availability conditions of this Rate Schedule. For facilities with Wholesale Charging Load, Critical Service Load and Station Service behind one PCC, a minimum of two meters is required, with one meter at the PCC (“PCC meter”) and a second meter positioned electrically in series behind the PCC meter and measuring only Wholesale Charging Load, including Critical Service Load. The Company may require a dedicated Station Service meter. The Customer shall be responsible for the costs incurred by the Company for the purchase, installation, operation, maintenance, testing, repair, and replacement of metering and data acquisition equipment, in accordance with the ISA. 7.2 A properly identified and authorized representative of the Company shall have the right to gain access at all reasonable times and intervals for the purpose of reading, installing, examining, testing, repairing, replacing, or removing the Company’s meters, meter reading devices, wires, or other electrical equipment and appliances, or of discontinuing service, in accordance with Company policy, in effect from time to time, and the Customer shall not prevent or hinder the Company’s access. 7.3 If a customer receives unmetered service as the result of any tampering with the meter or other Company equipment, the Company shall take appropriate corrective action including, but not limited to, making changes in the meter or other equipment and rebilling the Customer. The Customer will be held responsible to the Company for any use of electricity that occurs beyond the point of meter installation. 8. Rates and Charges 8.1 The Basic Rates are set forth in the tables below. Different Basic Rates are provided for Customers taking service under Subschedule 1 and Subschedule 2. (i) For WDS Rate Classes B-1 and B-5, the Monthly WDS Charge equals Customer Charge plus Distribution Energy Charge plus Transmission Energy Charge. (ii) For WDS Rate Classes M-1, M-2, and D-4, the Monthly WDS Charge equals Customer Charge plus Distribution Demand plus Transmission Demand Charge. (iii) For WDS Rate Classes WDS T-1 Subtrans and WDS T-1 Trans, the Monthly WDS Charge equals Customer Charge plus Distribution Energy Charge plus Transmission Demand Charge. 8.2 The minimum charge for any month is the Customer Charge plus the Distribution Demand Charge (if any) plus the Transmission Demand Charge (if any). 8.3 Seasons: The Winter season is from November through February. The Non-Winter season is from March through October. 8.4 Time Periods – Weekdays: The On-Peak time period is from 7 a.m. to 12 p.m. and 4 p.m. to 8 p.m. The Shoulder time period is from 12 p.m. to 4 p.m. The Off-Peak time period is from 8 p.m. to 7 a.m. All time periods are expressed as Eastern Prevailing Time. 8.5 Time Periods – Weekends: The Shoulder time period is from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. The Off-Peak time period is from 8 p.m. to 7 a.m. All time periods are expressed as Eastern Prevailing Time. 8.6 Demand: The demand will be determined by a suitable meter or meters installed and maintained by the Company. The demand used for billing will be as follows: (i) For WDS Rate Classes M-1 and M-2: The average load during the fifteen (15) minute period of maximum use in the current month, subject to a minimum value of 25 kW; (ii) For WDS Rate Class D-4: The average load during the fifteen (15) minute period of maximum use in the current month, subject to a minimum value of 500 kW; (iii) For WDS Rate Class WDS T-1 Subtrans and WDS T-1 Trans electing Non-Coincident Peak Demand billing: The average load during the fifteen (15) minute period of maximum use in the current month, subject to a minimum value of 500 kW; (iv) For WDS Rate Class WDS T-1 Subtrans and WDS T-1 Trans electing Coincident Peak Demand billing: The average load during the sixty (60) minute period coincident with each monthly Bangor Hydro District system peak load (subject to no minimum value). 8.7 Transmission Service: Per FERC Order No. 841 which resulted in revisions to the ISO-NE Tariff, Section II.21.3 and Schedule 21, Section II.9, Company has set the allocated Regional Network Service and Local Network Service cost components to zero for the Basic Rates set forth above. 8.8 If the Customer fails to respond to established emergency load shedding and curtailment procedures to relieve emergencies on the Distribution System and energy is delivered to its Wholesale Charging Load, the Customer shall pay, in addition to any other charges for service hereunder, a penalty charge equal to two times the Monthly Demand Charge for each occurrence in the month in which such failure to respond occurred, or the Company may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service under this Rate Schedule but shall not terminate service until FERC so accepts any such termination request. 8.9 Unreserved Use Penalties: Any Customer that elects to take service under Subschedule 2 but, during any month of the period covered by such election, makes any sales of energy while not under ISO-NE dispatch shall incur an Unreserved Use Penalty equal to twice the Transmission Demand Charge that it otherwise would have paid if it took service under Subschedule 1, in addition to all other charges set forth in Subschedule 1. This Unreserved Use Penalty shall be assessed starting with the first month in which the Customer made sales of energy while not under ISO-NE dispatch notwithstanding its election to take service under Subschedule 2. In addition, the Customer shall be deemed to have elected to take service under Subschedule 1 as of said month and for the next 11 months at which time the Customer can make an election as to which rate, but this deemed election shall not relieve the Customer from the payment of the foregoing Unreserved Use Penalties. 9. Billing and Payment 9.1 Bills will be rendered once each billing period, defined as the time period between two consecutive monthly meter readings or estimates of such monthly meter readings. The standard billing period is thirty (30) days. In the event that a period between bills is less twenty-six (26) days or more than thirty-four (34) days, the Company will prorate billing to reflect a thirty (30) day billing period. The Customer shall pay the invoice within twenty-five (25) days of receipt. If delivery is through more than one meter, the Monthly WDS Charge for service through each meter shall be computed separately under this rate. 9.2 Interest on any unpaid amounts (including amounts placed in escrow) shall be calculated in accordance with the methodology specified for interest on refunds in the FERC’s regulations at 18 C.F.R. § 35.19a(a)(2)(iii). Interest on delinquent amounts shall be calculated from the due date of the bill to the date of payment. When payments are made by mail, bills shall be considered as having been paid on the date of receipt by the Company. 9.3 In the event the Customer fails, for any reason other than a billing dispute as described below, to make payment to the Company on or before the due date as described in Section 10.1 above, and such failure of payment is not corrected within thirty (30) calendar days after the Company notifies the Customer to cure such failure, a default by the Customer shall be deemed to exist. Upon the occurrence of a default, the Company may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service under this Rate Schedule but shall not terminate service until FERC so accepts any such termination request. 9.4 In the event of a billing dispute between the Company and the Customer, the Company will continue to provide service under this Rate Schedule as long as the Customer (i) continues to make all payments not in dispute, and (ii) pays into an independent escrow account (established in accordance with a mutually agreed upon escrow agreement) the portion of the invoice in dispute, pending resolution of such dispute. If the Customer fails to meet these two requirements for continuation of service, then the Company may provide notice to the Customer of its intention to suspend service in no less than sixty (60) days. Upon final resolution of the dispute, in accordance with procedures set forth in Section 14 of this Rate Schedule, if a refund is due to either Party, the Company or the Customer, as appropriate, shall make such refund in accordance with Section 8.2 and within ten (10) business days of such resolution. 10. Characteristics of WDS 10.1 Company Responsibilities. The Company will plan, construct, operate and maintain its Distribution System in accordance with Good Utility Practice in order to provide the Customer with WDS over the Distribution System. The Company shall include the Customer’s Wholesale Charging Load and Critical Service Load in its Distribution System planning and shall, consistent with Good Utility Practice, endeavor to construct and place into service sufficient Distribution System facilities to deliver the Wholesale Charging Load on a basis comparable to the Company’s delivery of power to Company’s retail customers, subject to the operational parameters, if any, set forth in the ISA. 10.2 Self Supply of Station Load. An ESF may also discharge stored energy received under this Rate Schedule to serve qualified Station Service loads, as defined in the Company’s technical standards and associated with Stand Alone facilities, if such loads are located behind the same PCC as the ESF. Any energy for Station Service that is procured directly from the Distribution System (i.e., not served through energy discharged from the ESF) will be billed at the applicable retail rate. 10.3 Load Shedding and Curtailment of WDS. In addition to the Company’s ability to disconnect an ESF for Customer’s failure to pay an invoice in Section 10.3 above, a Customer under this Rate Schedule shall be subject to the procedures for disconnection, load reduction, and curtailment as determined necessary by the Company and consistent with Good Utility Practice. 10.4 Scheduling of WDS. Separate schedules for WDS shall not be required under this Rate Schedule. In transmission schedules submitted to the ISO-NE, the Customer shall include its Wholesale Charging Load, only if required to do so under the ISO-NE Tariff. 10.5 Conflict With ISO-NE Tariff. If a Customer identifies a conflict between this Rate Schedule and the ISO-NE Tariff, the Company and the Customer shall make good-faith efforts to resolve the conflict. If the Parties are unable to informally resolve the conflict, the Parties may use the Dispute Resolution Procedures set forth in Section 12 of this Rate Schedule. 10.6 Conflicting Operating Instructions. In the event a Customer receives conflicting operating instructions from the ISO- NE and the Company, the Customer shall adhere first to the conditions of its ISA with the Company and applicable tariffs approved by the MPUC. Otherwise, the Customer shall adhere to applicable ISO-NE Tariff provisions and follow the ISO-NE’s instructions. In no event shall a Customer be required to follow operating instructions from the ISO-NE if following those instructions would knowingly jeopardize human safety, including by jeopardizing the safety and reliability of the Distribution System through violation of the Customer’s ISA. The Company shall not be liable for money damages or other compensation to the Customer for issuing an operating instruction that overrides an ISO dispatch order or operating instruction unless the Company’s action has been found to result from its gross negligence or willful misconduct. 11. Force Majeure 11.1 Neither the Company nor the Customer will be considered in default as to any obligation under this Rate Schedule or the WDSA if prevented from fulfilling the obligation due to an event of Force Majeure; provided that no event of Force Majeure affecting either Party shall excuse that Party from making payments that it is obligated to make in this Rate Schedule. However, a Party whose performance under this Rate Schedule is hindered by an event of Force Majeure shall make all reasonable efforts to perform its obligations under this Rate Schedule and shall promptly notify the other Party of the commencement and end of each Force Majeure event. 12. Dispute Resolution Procedures 12.1 Internal Dispute Resolution Procedures Any dispute between a Customer and the Company involving WDS under this Rate Schedule (excluding applications for service terminations under Section 8.3 herein or rate changes or other changes to this Rate Schedule, or to any WDSA entered into under this Rate Schedule, which shall be presented directly to FERC for resolution) shall be referred to a designated senior representative of the Company and a senior representative of the Customer for resolution on an informal basis as promptly as practicable. In the event the designated representatives are unable to resolve the dispute within thirty (30) days by mutual agreement, such dispute may be submitted to arbitration and resolved in accordance with the arbitration procedures set forth in Section I.6 of the ISO-NE Tariff. 12.2 Rights under the Federal Power Act Nothing in this section shall restrict the rights of any party to file a complaint with the FERC or seek any other available remedy under relevant provisions of the Federal Power Act. 13. Limitation of Liability 13.1 The Company shall not be liable for money damages or other compensation to the Customer for actions or omissions by the Company in performing its obligations under this Rate Schedule or the WDSA, except to the extent such act or omission by the Company is found to result from its gross negligence or willful misconduct. To the extent the Customer alleges claims against the Company, the Customer may only look to the assets of the Company for the enforcement of such claims and may not seek to enforce any claims against the directors, members, shareholders, officers, employees or agents of the Company or affiliate of either which, the Customer acknowledges and agrees, have no personal or other liability for obligations of the Company by reason of their status as directors, members, shareholders, officers, employees or agents of the Company or affiliate of either. 13.2 In no event shall either Party, their respective officers, directors, employees, agents, successors or assigns or their affiliates be liable to the other Party for any incidental, consequential, multiple or punitive damages, loss of revenues or profits, attorneys fees or costs arising out of, or connected in any way with, performance or nonperformance of this Rate Schedule or the WDSA. 13.3 The provisions of this Section shall survive termination, cancellation, suspension, completion or expiration of this Rate Schedule or the WDSA. 14. Indemnification 14.1 The Customer shall at all times indemnify, defend, and save the Company, its directors, officers, members, employees, agents, successors and assigns from any and all damages, losses, claims and liabilities by or to third parties arising out of or resulting from the performance by the Company hereunder, any bankruptcy filings made by the Customer, or the actions or omissions of the Customer in connection with this Rate Schedule and the WDSA, except in the case of gross negligence or willful misconduct by the Company, its directors, officers, members, employees or agents. The amount of any indemnity payment hereunder shall be reduced (including, without limitation, retroactively) by any insurance proceeds or other amounts recovered by the indemnified party in respect of the indemnified action, claim, demand, cost, damage or liability. For the purposes of this Section, the term “third parties” includes without limitation, customers under this Rate Schedule, ISO-NE and any other Transmission Owners. 15. Corporate Act and Obligation 15.1 This Rate Schedule and the WDSA are the corporate act and obligation of the Customer and the Company and shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of the Parties hereto and their successors and assigns. Any claim hereunder against any stockholder, director, officer, or member of the board of either Party, in such capacity, is expressly waived. 16. Regulatory Filings 16.1 Nothing contained in this Rate Schedule or the WDSA shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the Company or any Customer to unilaterally make application to the FERC under Section 205 or Section 206 of the Federal Power Act, and FERC’s rules and regulations promulgated thereunder, for a change in this Rate Schedule (including the rates, terms and conditions, charges, classification of service set forth herein) or the WDSA. 16.2 The standard of review that shall apply in any proceeding initiated by either Party or FERC acting sua sponte to seek a change in the rates, terms or conditions of this Rate Schedule shall be the ordinary “just and reasonable” standard of review, and not the “public interest” standard of review. 16.3 Unless the Parties agree to otherwise in writing, the standard of review for any proposed changes sought by any Party to a WDSA shall be the “public interest” standard of review set forth in United Gas Pipe Line Co. v. Mobile Gas Services Corp., 350 U.S. 332 (1956) and Federal Power Commission v. Sierra Pacific Power Co., 350 U.S. 348 (1956), as clarified in Morgan Stanley Capital Group Inc. v. Pub. Util. Dist. No. 1, 554 U.S. 527 (2008). 17. Governing Law 17.1 Except as otherwise provided by federal law, this Rate Schedule and the WDSA shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the State of Maine. 18. Miscellaneous 18.1 Notices. Any notice, request, demand or statement required to be given by either Party to the other in connection with this Rate Schedule or a WDSA shall be given in writing and shall be sent by email (read receipt requested), registered or certified mail (return receipt requested and postage prepaid), by hand delivery, or by overnight delivery, with acknowledged receipt of delivery. Notice shall be deemed given at the date of acceptance or refusal of acceptance shown on such receipt. Any notice, request or demand pertaining to matters of an operating nature, which matters do not include requests for additional WDS or modified WDS under this Rate Schedule and the WDSA, may be served in person or by United States mail, messenger, telephone, email, or orally, as circumstances dictate, to the person designated in writing by the Party as its representative for such purposes in the WDSA; provided that should the same not be written, confirmation thereof shall be made in writing as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter, upon request of the Party being served. 18.2 Headings. The descriptive headings of the various sections of this Rate Schedule have been inserted for convenience of reference only and shall in no way define, modify or restrict any of the terms and provisions thereof. 18.3 Other Instruments. From time to time after the execution of the WDSA, the Parties may execute such instruments, upon the request of the other, as may be necessary or appropriate, to carry out the intent of this Rate Schedule and the WDSA. 18.4 Severability. Any provision of this Rate Schedule or the Customer’s WDSA rendered unlawful by a court of law or regulatory agency with jurisdiction will not otherwise affect the lawful obligations under this Rate Schedule and the Customer’s WDSA. 18.5 Third-Party Beneficiaries. This Rate Schedule and WDSA are not intended to and shall not create rights of any character whatsoever in favor of any person, corporation, association, or entity other than the Parties, and the rights and obligations herein assumed are solely for the use and benefit of the Parties. 18.6 No Dedication. Any undertaking by one Party to the other under any provisions of this Rate Schedule and the WDSA shall not constitute the dedication of the electric system, or any portion thereof, of any Party to the public or to the other Party, and it is understood and agreed that any such undertaking by any Party shall cease upon termination of the Agreement. 18.7 Entire Agreement. By execution of a WDSA accepting the provision of WDS under the terms and conditions set forth in this Rate Schedule, the Parties intend for this Rate Schedule and WDSA to replace and supersede all current or prior agreements for WDS. This Rate Schedule and WDSA supersede all prior agreements, discussion, communications, and correspondence for WDS between Company and Customer, and any of their predecessors, and represent the entire understanding between Company and Customer. 18.8 Interpretation. For the purpose of interpreting this Rate Schedule and the WDSA, to the extent that there exists any conflict between the provisions of this Agreement and the provisions of the ISO-NE Tariff, the provisions of this Rate Schedule and WDSA shall prevail. 18.9 Breach. Company may terminate Customer’s WDSA upon breach by Customer of any material term of this Rate Schedule after ninety (90) days’ written notice to Customer unless Customer cures its breach within that period. If the breach is not cured in thirty (30) days after a notice of breach, the Company may initiate a proceeding with FERC to terminate service but shall not terminate service until FERC so accepts any such termination request.
